BC-250 / Cyan Skillfish: enable GFX clock gating (idle power)

AMD ships cyan skillfish (GC 10.1.3/4) with cg_flags=0 and leaves its IP
revisions out of every set_clockgating_state switch, so no clock ever
gates at idle (~20 W on VDDCR_GFX at 0% activity). This layer enables ONLY
the GFX MGCG/CGCG path: the silicon is navi1x-generation GC 10.1, so this
reuses the register programming AMD already validated on Navi10 (10.1.10)
and its siblings (10.1.1/10.1.2) — nothing here touches an unvalidated
register map. It sets the two GFX flags and adds 10.1.3/4 to the gfx_v10
set_clockgating_state switch so the flags actually program.

The memory/SDMA/NBIO paths (MC, ATHUB, SDMA, HDP, NBIF) are split out into
bc250-cg-flags-unvalidated.patch: those fold cyan skillfish's IP revisions
into a *different* revision's register programming and are NOT known-safe
(AMD ships cyan skillfish its own SDMA golden-settings table, so its
register map is demonstrably distinct). Keep them opt-in.

Each update func is flag-gated, so features can be bisected at boot with
amdgpu.cg_mask (GFX-only: 0x5).

The navi1x MGCG TCP_CTRL workaround is deliberately NOT applied: its
register lists encode Navi10/12 WGP topology. If GFX misbehaves under
load with MGCG, drop bit 0 via cg_mask before suspecting anything else.

--- a/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/nv.c
+++ b/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/nv.c
@@ -870,7 +870,8 @@
 		break;
 	case IP_VERSION(10, 1, 3):
 	case IP_VERSION(10, 1, 4):
-		adev->cg_flags = 0;
+		adev->cg_flags = AMD_CG_SUPPORT_GFX_MGCG |
+			AMD_CG_SUPPORT_GFX_CGCG;
 		adev->pg_flags = 0;
 		adev->external_rev_id = adev->rev_id + 0x82;
 		break;
--- a/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/gfx_v10_0.c
+++ b/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/gfx_v10_0.c
@@ -8495,6 +8495,8 @@
 	case IP_VERSION(10, 1, 10):
 	case IP_VERSION(10, 1, 1):
 	case IP_VERSION(10, 1, 2):
+	case IP_VERSION(10, 1, 3):
+	case IP_VERSION(10, 1, 4):
 	case IP_VERSION(10, 3, 0):
 	case IP_VERSION(10, 3, 2):
 	case IP_VERSION(10, 3, 1):
